description.text:
Since finishing my spool box my desk lamp no longer lights the platform.
I looked at lighting in Thingiverse but the solutions required parts I didnt have or the Mk4 Plastruder.
So heres my attempt using two led torches from the local store, some 15A fuse wire, and a 9.8 ohm resistor.
WARNING DO NOT CONNECT TO YOUR POWER SUPPLY WITHOUT A CURRENT LIMITING RESISTOR, IT WILL RESULT IN AT LEAST 1AMP CURRENT DRAW. (Warm cables to say the least).
And for the electrical engineers out there, yes you are not supposed to connect LEDS in parallel without individual resistors.
Although you can get away with it if they are the same type of LEDS in my mind (thus I bought 2 off same type torches).

Print out the plastic thing.
Remove LED heads from torches, (they push out the front, so a bolt or somet that is longer than the torch body is ideal to push it out against the floor, maybe a bit of tapping with a hammer too).
With soldering iron and flat screwdriver price out your leds from the PCB, its easier if you have someone to hold the PCB or use a vice.
Push the LED's into the plastic thing, YOU WILL NOTICE A FLAT EDGE ON YOUR LEDS EDGE - FACE THIS TO THE CENTER/CENTRE OF THE THINGY. This will put the cathode (negative legs) all around the inside rim.
(You might have to ream the holes a little, I used a 4.8mm drill bit)
Using the fuse wire or what ever wire you got solder the inside ring and seperately the outside ring of legs (see picture). I found putting a loop around each LED pin stub a help, but makes replacement of a single LED a pain.
Connect your cable and insulate so it cant short (remember you risk your power supply.
Connect the other end, again see picture, I worked out that the 9.8ohm resistor should result in about 158mA (0.8W) consumption (measured about 120mA). Now you may spot that I used a 1/4W resistor (its all I had), if you can, use at least a 1/2Watt. Mine works but gets a little warm, its been running now 12Hrs and seems stable.
Please remember though you must use a limiting resistor.
Test, I used the battery pack out of one of the torches to test the ring's prior to fitting the resister, possibly a good idea as I had fitted one the wrong way round and another I had knackered when removing from the PCB.
Plug into your power supply, making sure you connect positive (outer ring) to red wire on molex connector (+5V) and negative (inner ring) to black on molex connector.
Initially just keep your eyes open make sure you dont let the magic smoke out and check your cables/resistor are not getting warm/hot.
If ok, remove the plastruder head from Z axis table, slide plastic thing into the U slot with the pin going to the hole drilled in the table, it should just pop in to the hole holding the lights in place.
Run your cable as suits, and thats it.
My system has the thermal tape fitted, I would not suggest using this thingy on an un-insulated head.

description.text:
This drawing is less demanding of plotting precision than an earlier, similar version I have posted.  This version fully draws each local region of the egg before moving on to the next region.  While this makes the plotting time a bit slower (but not by much), it reduces the amount of plotting precision needed.  (The prior version of this drawing was optimized for speed but made the egg go through many full back and forth revolutions.)
If you still have plotting precision issues, you can slightly stretch the drawing horizontally by, say, 5 pixels.  (If that's not enough, then iterate by stretching again.)  Just select layer "2 - black", select all in layer, and then use Object > Transform.  In the Transform sub-window, use the "Scale" tab and set the units to "px" (pixels).  You may see that the initial width isn't exactly 3200 pixels: that's because (1) the drawing is wider than 3200 pixels as it wraps around the egg, and (2) Inkscape takes into account the stroke width of the lines.
Alternatively, you can remove a column or two from the drawing if you are having plotting precision issues.  The result still looks quite nice.
For plotting on spheres, you will need to rescale the vertical component of the drawing: it is presently squashed vertically so as to make it suitable for plotting on eggs.  Rescale the vertical dimension by 100% / (0.666666 * 0.95) or 157.89%.
The SVG files pattern-20.svg and pattern-16.svg have, respectively, 20 or 16 "stars" running horizontally around the egg.  Thus the -20 file has more stars.  The interactive Python script pattern.py may be used to generate additional SVG files with whatever density of stars you'd like, and with or without vertical compression for eggs.

The supplied SVG files contain the actual drawing in layer 2, "2 - black".  To aid in framing the drawing on your egg, layer 1, "1 - test", contains two short horizontal lines at y=0 and y=800.  You can draw layer 1 first (with or without a pen), to get your drawing page framed on your egg.  Then draw layer 2 to actually plot the drawing.
Be sure that "Egg axis (x) wraps around" is checked in the Options tab of the Eggbot Control extension.  This drawing relies on wrapping.

For my 3D Printer Reviews at http://nicklievendag.com I've printed an army of Yoda Busts over the past months - you probably have a few yourself as well! So I decided to print him a Christmas Hat! It's designed to perfectly fit the Yoda Bust by chylld (http://thingiverse.com/thing:14104) but might also fit other similar versions. Pictured are the Yoda bust at 200% and 100% scale. It's designed to be printed with two colors on a single extruder 3D printer (see instructions)

It's designed to be printed in two colors with a single extruder 3D printer. Depending on your printer, temperature and material, you might need to print the hat at 101% to make it fit nicely. Most printers allow you to pause the print process manually, switch filament, and resume printing. Some printers allow you to pre-program a pause height. I used this technique (Pause @Zpos) on the ZYYX I Reviewed on http://nicklievendag.com/zyyx-3d-printer-review-part-1. For the 100% version with raft I set the pause height at 12.4 mm. You will need to print supports, but only for the inside of the hat - the arch on the outside doesn't need support (set your overhang angle so they're not generated there). Depending on your printer, you might need to use a Raft to increase adhesion for the little white ball. You might need to print this very slowly to print the bottom half of the little white ball nicely.

title: Wades adapter plate for Printrbot Plus Z-X Upgrade

description.text:
Still have 3mm filament that you want to use with your Printrbot Plus v2.1 with the Z-X Upgrade?  This adapter replaces the standard baseplate (using Direct Drive extruder) with one that lets you mount the tried & true Wades Extruder.  
I created this after having continual poor performance using the Direct Drive Extruder with the 3mm Geared Stepper motor, yet still wanted to use up the rest of my 3mm filament before moving on to 1.75mm.   
It works well, and the good thing is that I only lost 25mm of print width!

• Print new baseplate.
  • Insert captured nuts on bottom of the new plate, used for mounting the wades extruder.
  • Remove old baseplate (detach belt, fan mount, electrical connections, detach from bearing blocks).
  • Unscrew the screw on the bottom of the bearing block closest to the auto-leveling sensor on the sensor mount. Loosen the other screw and swing the sensor out away from the baseplate.
  • If reusing the extruder motor, then detach it from the direct drive extruder & reattach to the wades extruder.
  • Attach fan mount to new baseplate. (May have to file the holes slightly)
  • Attach the new baseplate to the bearing blocks
  • Attach the Wades Extruder. Use shorter bolts so they do not extend past the captured nuts, and leave them loose. You need to notch the base of the extruder to fit over the right hand side bolts which fasten the baseplate to the bearing blocks (see photo). In order to accommodate the bolt head you'll also need to reverse a bolt which holds together the extruder (typically driven in from right side - now drive in from left side)
  • Slide the hot end up through the bottom and attach to extruder. Connect the hot end electrical connectors and route through the notch as before, though connector bodies will remain below the adapter plate.
  • You can now tighten down the extruder to the baseplate.
  • Swing the auto leveling sensor back in position and attach.
  • Attach the belt & tension accordingly.
    You may want to mount a small vertical tab of some sort to one of the baseplate mounting bolts on the top left side of the baseplate that you can then use to tie off the wires to keep them out of the gears (see photo).
    • You're now reassembled & after a few adjustments will be ready to Go!
  • Change Extruder steps using the M92 gcode command. The standard setting for the Wades Extruder is E590.
  • Change Max-X position using the M211 gcode command. (My max-x went from X190 to X165)

  • Save these new settings using the M500 gcode command.

  • The hot end is now at a different height, so you need to re-calibrate your auto leveling sensor.

  • Change X-Max & Print Area Width in Repetier-Host Printer Settings/Printer Shape

description.text:
Update: I have now got around to printing this and the M was way too small and also didn't even fit. No one told me, but now I fixed it.  
The only thing I changed from the original "Pokeball, with magnetic clasp" was the lid.  
Print the Lid, M, BumpTopLeft and BumpTopRigh (right/left with button facing towards you). The two Bump files in theory should be the same but just in case I provided both.  
After printing the parts you should be able to easily assemble the lid. From there glue the button into the button holder. Then glue the button assembly and the ring to the bottom with the hinge in place as you glue the ring down. Then snap the hinge into the lid.  
You will need 2 magnets (1/4" X 1/16") and just glue them in place too.  
Tip: Print your bottom piece at a higher in fill percentage, around 40-50% and then all the other parts at 5-10%. That way it will be bottom heavy and not roll around as much.

description.text: This is a printable Tesla Turbine which uses compact discs (or DVDs) as the turbine blades. It is configured for 10 discs, each of which must have a small triangular notch cut into the inner hole to mate with corresponding grooves on the shaft--the grooves are rifled in such a way that the discs are compressed when it spins. Rather than drill holes in the discs for outflow as done in some designs, in this case, the shaft is hollow and serves as the outlet channel. I had intended to make this 100% printable and able to be assembled without additional materials (e.g. glue, bolts), but the clips are insufficient and it leaked a lot on the first try. I resorted to superglue sealant for the example shown in the video (http://youtu.be/p5A7_m81X90). The goal is to couple this with my cordless drill as a generator though I have not tried that just yet and am not certain this will have enough torque--though the 25:1 differential bumps it up for sure. The flow area of the center shaft appears to be insufficient as you can see the internal pressure is high enough that some flow is pushed out through the bearing. I hope to continue to work on this and improve the design, but thought I would share at this point. It might be fun to make another version which uses hard disk platters--these have a large central opening (and more mass) which would allow for more flow in this hollow-shaft configuration. This design makes use of the awesome gear bearing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:53451) and differential bearing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:59075) scripts provided by Emmett as well as a garden hose fitting Thing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10189) modified by me with a hose barb (for 3/8" ID hose).

Everything should print without need for supports. The inletManifold prints vertically with the flat side down and the hose barb pointing up. Shaft prints with the female hex end downward.
Tabs on the large main case parts can be cut off after printing.
You will need to print 10 spacers, one for each disc. Assemble with a spacer first onto the shaft with flat side toward the male hex end (small bearing side) followed by a triangle-notched CD, a spacer, another CD, etc.
I also cut a couple of the posts in the outlet side of the shaft (as seen in the picture) to widen the flow area.
You will need some sort of washer inside the hose fitting to attach to your faucet or hose. I just cut one out of a piece of rubber.
The pull starter may not be required--at least I didn't end up needing it once I sealed the housing well. Your mileage may vary. NOTE: A small hole and setscrew (notice small black screw in video) is required to secure the input side of the differential bearing otherwise it will spin around when resistance is place on the output side. I plan to add a notch to the bearing case and a rib to the side of the bearing at some point to fix the bearing and eliminate the need for this screw.

description.text:
This air duct is for a radial fan (Jtron 40210020), directing air flow just below the nozzle for better cooling of plastic as it is deposited on a part in progress.  
I made this after upgrading my Prusa i3 to an E3D V6 hot end, replacing my previous design for the J-Head. The fan duct attaches directly to the hot end's own small fan using the bottom two screws.  
It has the shape of a donut and ocarina-style holes for directing air flow, hence the name.  
The OpenSCAD file is included so that you can adapt the design to a different fan, change the mounting style, etc. (Mind the orientation of the part in OpenSCAD, it is 90 degrees from what it should be, due to the orientation of the E3D models I used.)

I print all these pieces in ABS (for heat resistance), and I just acetone-weld the headlamp mount to the fan shroud. Clearances tested only with "stock" configuration (J-head and 40x40x10mm fan). Ring orientation. Note the location of the wire solder point indentation, and insert LED ring accordingly, for a flush fit. If you use a different ring, you may have to edit the source (included STL has indentations for chip resistors and wire solder point of the linked, 24-LED ring).

Cover for use to mount an on/off switch and keep little fingers from touching the 110V terminals when plugged in.

I use a 18V supply for my Reprap (to get the heated bed and glass up to temp for ABS).  It is the standard metal frame supply you can find on eBay and the like for $55 out of the far east.  This cover slips on the front to provide a location to mount a switch and has text formed in the surface to label the On/Off.  First print, then mount a standard 5 amp toggle switch you can get from Digikey or Radio Shack and slip in over the front of the terminal area.  You will need to drill pilot holes for mounting screws to secure the cover to the supplies side wings.  Also drill holes for your 110 cord and DC wires that go to your printer.  (See pictures).  I use tie wraps on the inside of the cover on the cables to strain relief the cables from being pulled out.
Inventor Fusion file included so you can edit as you see fit.
